  <data name="MeasurementInterval" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>You can configure whether to measure each item, set the measurement time interval, and specify when to start the measurement.

Wind speed consumes the most power, and the chosen measurement interval significantly impacts the duration for which measurements can continue.

If the measurement start date and time are set to a past time relative to the current time, the measurement will begin immediately.

If you make any changes to these settings, you must send the updated configuration to overwrite the internal settings of the M-Logger.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="ShortMemo" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Entering text here will append it to the end of each measurement data entry.
This can be useful for adding notes to record when measurement conditions were changed.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="StartLogging" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Options for Storing Measured Data

Phone:
Store the data internally on this iPhone or Android device.

PC:
Transmit the data using Zigbee to a PC or Raspberry Pi equipped with an XBee module.

Flash:
Write the data to the M-Logger's built-in flash memory.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="OtherSetting" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Hidden mode

Shaking the device unlocks additional maintenance options, including editing sensor correction factors and resetting the CO2 sensor calibration.

These operations directly affect measurement accuracy, so use them at your own risk.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="BatteryInfo" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Battery information

Voltage: VBAT measured at the AVR ADC. Updated when this screen opens.

Battery type: estimated from the initial voltage assuming fresh cells (Alkaline is above 2.85V, NiMH is at or below). If the displayed type does not match the actual cells you inserted, the cells may not be fresh or may be defective.

Estimated runtime: continuous measurement time for the current settings, assuming a fresh 2000mAh battery, with a 20% safety margin applied. Power consumption is determined by the chosen sensors and intervals — the wind sensor's heater wire dominates, so increasing the velocity interval has the largest impact on battery life.

This is a reference value. Actual runtime varies by about ±30% depending on temperature, self-discharge, and individual cell variation. The firmware will automatically stop logging if VBAT drops below 1.8V.</value>
  </data>
